<h2>Step 5: Configure Scheduling and Auto-Publishing</h2>
<p>With your writing pipeline and quality gate in place, you now need consistent delivery. Publishing 5 posts at once on Monday and nothing for the rest of the week sends mixed signals to search engines and readers.</p>
<p><strong>Set up your publishing schedule:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Choose your frequency.</strong> 2 to 3 posts per week for small businesses. 5 to 7 per week for aggressive growth. Daily publishing is ideal if your pipeline supports it.</li>
<li><strong>Pick optimal days and times.</strong> Tuesday through Thursday mornings tend to perform well for B2B audiences. Test and adjust based on your analytics.</li>
<li><strong>Use your CMS scheduler.</strong> WordPress, Webflow, and Ghost all let you set a publish date and time. The post goes live automatically.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>For WordPress specifically:</strong>
- Posts scheduled natively in the editor publish at the set time
- Plugins like PublishPress extend scheduling with editorial workflows
- The <a href="https://developer.wordpress.org/rest-api/">WordPress REST API</a> allows external tools to create and schedule posts programmatically</p>
